GOAL: FLASK CONTAINER TALKS TO ANOTHER CONTAINER

    STEP 1: CREATE A NETWORK
        [docker network create my-network]
        this creates a private network for the containers
    
    
    STEP 2 RUN FIRST CONTAINER(database)
        [docker run -d \
        --name db \
        --network my-network \
         -e POSTGRES_PASSWORD=example \
        postgres]
        this starts the "POSTGRES" Container, names it db and connects it to "my-network" 
    
    
    STEP 3 PREPARE YOUR FLASK APP
        your app.py must look like this:
        [from flask import Flask

        app = Flask(__name__)

        @app.route("/")
        def home():
        return "Flask connected to Docker network!"

        if __name__ == "__main__":
        app.run(host="0.0.0.0", port=5001)]

    STEP 4 - BUILD FLASK IMAGE
        [docker build -t flask-app .]
    
    STEP 5 RUN FLASK CONTAINER
        [docker run -d \
        --name web \
        --network my-network \
        -p 5001:5001 \
        flask-app]
    This runs app.py inside a container, names it web and connects it to the same network 

    STEP 6 - LINK CONTAINERS
        inside the flask app"app.py", you connect the database like this
        [db_host = "db"]
        WHY: docker automatically provides DNS 
        db - resolvesto database container
        web - resolves to flask container
    
    STEP 7 - TEST COMMUNICATION
        enter flask container:
        [docker exec -it web bash]
        then test it :
        [ping db]
        if it worked containers are linked

    TEST 8 - TEST YOUR APP
        open: http://localhost:5001
    

    COMMON MISTAKES:
        using localhost: 
        - points to itself, not other containers 
        Not using same network
        - Containers wont see each other
        Flask not using 0.0.0.0
        - App wont be accessible 


